data.value: Data hiding is the transmission of a secret message hidden within an ordinary carrier without revealing its existence. The container (cover file) may be a digital still image, audio file, or media file. Once the secret message has been embedded, it may be transferred across insecure lines or posted in public places. Usually, the data rate of covert data transmission using data hiding is low in order to keep the covert data imperceptible within the cover medium. This data rate is somewhat proportional to the volume of the cover medium. For this reason, digital media is a convenient choice for data hiding. Nowadays, given the high degree of collaboration and cooperation in modern information systems such as emerging multimedia sensor networks, covert communications becomes a greater threat to forensic analysis than ever. It is imperative to investigate methods to detect and discourage covert communications such as data hiding in multimedia networks that acquire highly correlated data.
